Text Mining Lesson - Day 2¶

1. Part-of-speech tagging text¶

In text mining it can be useful to extract words that have a particular part of speech (POS) such as a noun or a verb. For example extracting all proper nouns can give use names and locations. This is done using a POS-tagger. The POS-tag of a word is a label of the word indicating its part of speech as well as grammatical categories such as tense, number (plural/singular) and case. POS tagging is the process of automatically determining the POS-tags of the tokens in a corpus.

In this lesson, we will use NLTKs averaged_perceptron_tagger as the POS-tagger. It uses the perceptron algorithm to predict which POS-tag is most likely given the word. We need to download the tagger in order to use it.

The POS-tagger outputs tokens tagged with their POS-tag. It uses the Penn Treebank POS tagset which is widely used for POS-tagging text.

POS-tagging text is very useful when analysing a corpus or document and will allow us to do more indepth analysis and visualisations. In order to pos-tag using NLTK, you also have to import pos_tag from the tag package.

We are going to use the text from the US Presidential Inaugaral speeches. This is a data set that we can download from NLTK.

2. Named Entity Recognition¶

Named entiy recognition (NER) or named entity tagging is a way of locating and classifying named entities in text (e.g. names of people, locations and organisations). NER can be used to identity networks of people mentioned in data or as the first step towards geo-parsing text, i.e. extracting and disambiguating locations mentioned in text.

There are several off-the-shelf NER taggers that we can use. Here we will be using the Standford NER tagger (Finkel, Grenager, Manning (ACL 2005)). To use it you need to first download it on your computer from:

https://nlp.stanford.edu/software/stanford-ner-2018-10-16.zip

Check where the stanford-ner-2018-10-16 directory was download to. E.g. on Mac it's typically in the ~/Downloads directory. The directory path to the Standford tagger is needed to be able to run it.

To run the Standford NER Tagger using NLTK you first need to import its NLTK class and then call it by specifying its model which in my case is: /Users/balex/Downloads/stanford-ner-2018-1016/classifiers/english.all.3class.distsim.crf.ser.gz (but you will need to change it!)

and the path to the standfor-ner.jar file (in my case):

/Users/balex/Downloads/stanford-ner-2018-10-16/stanford-ner.jar

These paths change depending on where you saved the tagger.

In [8]:
from nltk.tag import StanfordNERTagger

Function: In python we can define a function using the def keyword. A function is a block of code that can be called to complete a task. The name of the function is specified after def and the parameters passed to the function are specified in round brackets after the name. A function can return data as a result.

Below is a function which contains code that extracts multiword entities from the NER output. The code above gave us only single word entities (such as "Trump") but sometimes the entity is a multi-word name (such as "Donald Trump") and we want to extract the entire name and not just each word seperately. The get_entities() method is a way to group multi-word entities first and extract all entities from the text. It is quite a complicated piece of code but essential it takes as input a NER-tagged text and checks if the next token is also a named entity with the same NER-tag and if so it treats it as part of the same entity.

In [10]:
def get_entities(tagged_corpus):
    continuous_chunk = []
    current_chunk = []

    for token, tag in tagged_corpus:
        if tag != "O":
            current_chunk.append((token, tag))
        else:
            if current_chunk: # if the current chunk is not empty
                continuous_chunk.append(current_chunk)
                current_chunk = []
    # Flush the final current_chunk into the continuous_chunk, if any.
    if current_chunk:
        continuous_chunk.append(current_chunk)
        
    named_entities_str = [" ".join([token for token, tag in ne]) for ne in continuous_chunk]
    named_entities_str_tag = [(" ".join([token for token, tag in ne]), ne[0][1]) for ne in continuous_chunk]
    return named_entities_str_tag

Below is how we call the above function and how we would show the first 20 named entities which it returns:

3. Network of entities¶

You can use network visualisations to show how things are connected in data. Networks are often used for showing networks of people in social media. Today we'll use a network visualisation to display how all US presidents are connected in terms of the people they mention in their speeches.

To do that you'll first learn how to save data to a file. The content of file serves as the input to the network. Let's first create the content (fileContent) which we will write to a file. We'll be creating a csv (comma-separated file), meaning that each line contains different fields separated by a comma. The first line is the header which provides a name for each column in the file. The first column are the names of presidents and the second column the people mentioned in their speeches.

The president,person pairs are created by looping through each speech, extracting the name of each president from names of the speeches, NER-tagging each speech and extracting people names for each speech. For all people extracted from each speech, we then concatenate the fileContent variable with the president's name (president) and each person name (person) mentioned in his speech followed by a newline character ("\n") so that one pair is added per line.

Note: this next bit of code takes some time to create because each speech has to be NER-tagged individually. We're only printing out the first 30 lines but in total fileContent contains the header and 102 lines listing all the president,person pairs in this data.

In [15]:
header="president,person\n"
fileContent=header
for fileid in inaugural.fileids():
    president=fileid[5:-4]
    nertagged_words = st.tag(inaugural.words(fileid))
    named_entities=get_entities(nertagged_words)
    people = [string for (string, tag) in named_entities if (tag == 'PERSON')] 

    if len(people) > 0:
        for person in people:
            fileContent=fileContent + president + "," + person + "\n"
            
print(fileContent[:30])

president,person
Harrison,Jeff

To write to a file you need to use the open() method and specify the file's name and mode (in this case "w" for write to file). You can then use the write() method and specify the content of the file in brackets. Don't forget to close the file using close() once you're done.

In [16]:
f = open("presidents.csv", "w")
f.write(fileContent)
f.close()

We need to import two further packages to visualise a network. pandas is used to represent data frames. and networkx is needed to create a network.

The degree of a node in a network is the number of connections it has to other nodes. For example, the degree for "Reagan" can be calculated using the degree() method on initial network. We will use degree as a way of varying the node size of person nodes, people with a larger degree will be displayed bigger in the network.

In [22]:
g.degree("Reagan")
Out[22]:
20

The following bit of code draws the network. The first two lines set the size of the graph and the layout of the network.

After that the different nodes are drawn using differnt parameters for node_color and node_size. Then the edges and node labels are drawn and the title of the network is specified.

In [23]:
# setting the size of the network
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 16))

# you can choose different ways of laying out the network
layout = nx.spring_layout(g)

# go through every person name, ask the graph how many
# connections it has. Multiply that by 100 to get the circle size
person_size = [g.degree(person) * 100 for person in people]

# draw the people nodes
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(g, 
                       layout, 
                       nodelist=people,
                       node_color='mediumpurple',
                       node_size=person_size # a list of sizes, based on g.degree
                       )

# draw president nodes
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(g, layout, nodelist=presidents, node_color='wheat', node_size=100)

# popular presidents are ones which had more than one presidency
popular_president = [president for president in presidents if g.degree(president) > 1]

# draw popular president nodes
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(g, layout, nodelist=popular_president, node_color='orange', node_size=100)

# draw network edges
nx.draw_networkx_edges(g, layout, width=1, edge_color="#cccccc")

# draw node labels
nx.draw_networkx_labels(g, layout, font_size=12)

plt.axis('off')
plt.title("Presidents and people", fontsize=20)
plt.show()
